In this document we will go through an entire RNA-seq analysis workflow, from raw read files to statistical interpretation. We will use an example data set, described below. Note that to make things simpler, all commands will be run from inside R, but that everything that is within a system() call in fact invokes a “system command”, which is run outside of R (equivalent to running the command from the command line).

Set some paths

The first thing we need to do is to set paths to the software that will be used and to input and output folders, where data will be read and written.

The example data set

The example data set comes from an RNA-seq experiment wherein airway smooth muscle cells were treated with dexamethasone (see Himes 2014, PMID 24926665, data is deposited in Gene Expression Omnibus under accession GSE52778). Four human airway smooth muscle cell lines were treated with 1 micromolar dexamethasone for 18 hours. For each of the four cell lines, we have a treated and an untreated sample. All quantifications will be based on the Ensembl human reference genome, version GRCh37.75. Note that for a real analysis, you should typically use the most recent reference genome for your particular organism.

Raw data

Raw reads typically come as fastq files. Here we investigate what such a file looks like by printing the first few lines.

(cmd <- sprintf("head %s/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_1.fastq", data_dir))
## [1] "head /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/input/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_1.fastq"
system(cmd)

QC of raw data

Raw data quality control is typically done to check for low-quality data, remaining adapters, contamination, etc. One of the most popular software packages to do this is FastQC.

(cmd <- paste0('chmod +x ', path_to_fastqc))
## [1] "chmod +x /home/mholub/Software/FastQC/fastqc"
system(cmd)
(cmd <- paste0(path_to_fastqc, " -h"))
## [1] "/home/mholub/Software/FastQC/fastqc -h"
system(cmd)

Since we have so called paired-end reads (each cDNA fragment was sequenced from both ends), we have two fastq files for each sample, which are run through FastQC separately.

(cmd <- sprintf("%s -o %s/airway_chr18 %s/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_1.fastq", 
                path_to_fastqc,
                output_dir,
                data_dir))
## [1] "/home/mholub/Software/FastQC/fastqc -o /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/output/airway_chr18 /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/input/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_1.fastq"
system(cmd)
(cmd <- sprintf("%s -o %s/airway_chr18 %s/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_2.fastq", 
                path_to_fastqc,
                output_dir,
                data_dir))
## [1] "/home/mholub/Software/FastQC/fastqc -o /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/output/airway_chr18 /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/input/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_2.fastq"
system(cmd)

If necessary, fix QC problems

Most commonly, this involves trimming away sequencing adapters. More rarely, very low-quality sequences are excluded or trimmed. Some software for trimming reads are cutadapt, Trimmomatic, FASTX-toolkit and TrimGalore!

Reference files

Reference files are needed to infer the origin of the observed read sequences. There are several sources of such reference files, e.g. Ensembl, UCSC, or iGenome. An alternative is biomaRt. See a recent tutorial.

Genomic sequence

The genomic sequence is typically provided in fasta format.

system(sprintf("head %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.dna.chromosome.18.fa", 
               data_dir))
system(sprintf("wc -l %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.dna.chromosome.18.fa",
               data_dir))

Transcript sequences

Also the transcript sequences are typically stored in fasta format.

system(sprintf("head %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.cdna.chr18.fa", 
               data_dir))
system(sprintf("wc -l %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.cdna.chr18.fa",
               data_dir))
system(sprintf("grep '>' %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.cdna.chr18.fa | wc -l",
               data_dir))

Location of genomic features

The information about the genomic location of features such as exons or genes is typically provided in gtf (stricter, typically recommended) or gff format.

system(sprintf("head %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.chr18.gtf", data_dir))

Genome alignment-based quantification approach

There are various aligners that can be used to find the most likely origin of each sequencing read on the genome, e.g. HISAT2, STAR, or TopHat2. For genome alignment of RNA-seq data, it is important that the aligner allows gaps in the alignment (to accommodate reads spanning exon-exon junctions).

Index reference genome for use with HISAT2

Most aligners output alignments in either SAM or BAM (binary SAM) format.

system(sprintf("head %s/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_hisat2.sam", output_dir))

Convert sam file to binary bam file and sort alignments

samtools is the standard library for manipulating SAM/BAM files.

(cmd <- sprintf("%s view -b %s | %s sort -T tmp -O bam - > %s",
                path_to_samtools, 
                paste0(output_dir, "/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_hisat2.sam"),
                path_to_samtools, 
                paste0(output_dir, "/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_hisat2.bam")))
## [1] "/home/mholub/Software/samtools/bin/samtools view -b /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/output/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_hisat2.sam | /home/mholub/Software/samtools/bin/samtools sort -T tmp -O bam - > /home/mholub/RNAseq_temp/output/airway_chr18/SRR1039508_chr18_hisat2.bam"

Generate transcript-to-gene mapping

In order to perform gene-level analyses, we need to combine the transcript-level output from Salmon with information about which transcripts stem from the same gene locus, and summarize the estimated abundances on the gene level.

system(sprintf("head %s/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.cdna.ncrna.chr18.fa", output_dir))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(Biostrings))

## Read the fasta file in R using a function from the Biostrings package
cdna.ncrna <- readDNAStringSet(paste0(output_dir,
                                      "/airway_chr18/reference_chr18/Homo_sapiens.GRCh37.75.cdna.ncrna.chr18.fa"))

## Go through the sequence names and extract the required information
tx2gene <- data.frame(t(sapply(names(cdna.ncrna), function(nm) {
  tmp <- strsplit(nm, " ")[[1]]
  tx <- tmp[1]
  gene <- gsub("gene:", "", tmp[grep("^gene:", tmp)])
  c(tx = tx, gene = gene)
})), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
rownames(tx2gene) <- NULL

head(tx2gene)

Import abundance estimates into R and summarize on gene level

We parse the text files output by Salmon and summarize the data for all samples into one abundance matrix, using the tximport R package.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tximport))

Filter out lowly expressed genes

Different filter criteria are possible, but should be independent of the test statistic under the null hypothesis (in particular, should not involve use of the sample annotations).

cpm <- cpm(dge)
dge <- dge[which(rowSums(cpm > 0.5) > 4), , keep.lib.sizes = FALSE]
dge <- calcNormFactors(dge)
